occurrences.line_text: And Lordings curbe, that commons ouer-aw;
Then gan the Peoples cry and Commons sute,
Therewith containes his heauenly Common-weale,
Both to her selfe, and to her commonweale,
How to reforme that ragged common-weale:
Did commun breath and nouriture receaue?
To commun accidents still open layd,
Are bound with commun bond of frailtee,
To errant knights be commun: wondrous sore
And forth he comes into the commune hall,
Who well acquainted with that commune plight,
Vnworthie of the commune breathed aire,
With whom from tender dug of commune nourse,
It was my fortune commune to that age,
(For so that Castle hight by commune name)
For not as other wemens commune brood,
Of her chaste bodie, nor with commune food,
And that vncurteous Carle their commune foe
As countries cause, and commune foes disdayne.
When so in open place, and commune bord,
He fortun'd her to meet, with commune speach
That is the whole worlds commune remedy.
And euery one as commune good her handeled.
By any ridling skill, or commune wit.
And gaue him being, commune to them twaine:
Whiles thus they communed, lo farre away
That this is things compacte betwixt you two,
All which compacted made a goodly Diapase.
Perforce disparted their compacted gyre,
With comely compasse, and compacture strong,
And Pholoe fowle, when her to this he doth compaire.
And ouer him, art striuing to compaire
Liues ought, that to her linage may compaire,
Or Eden selfe, if ought with Eden mote compaire.
That neuer any mote with her compaire.
Of chastitie, none liuing may compaire:
With a faire knight to keepen companee,
From highest heauen, in gladsome companee,
Thensforth from her most beastly companie
Of proud Lucifera, and his owne companie.
Sweet loue such lewdnes bands from his faire companie.
Which when his other companie beheld,
And made good semblance to his companie,
So loth she was his companie for to forsake.
Him to recomfort with my companie.
Into a caue from companie exilde,
There came this knight, hauing in companie
Glad from his companie to be so sondred;
She wander should in companie of those,
And euery day, her companie to gaine,
And euer when him came in companie,
To common haunts, and companies frequent,
Where companing with feends and filthy Sprights,
He had a faire companion of his way,
Of her lewd parts to make companion;
Made her companion, and her lessoned
Was Amoret, companion of her care:
Companion she became, and so continued long.
And eke his deare companion of his care.
With two companions of like qualitie,
With these two lewd companions, and no more,
Such one was Idlenesse, first of this company.
Arrested all that courtly company,
And could not lacke her louers company,
Thenceforth he kept her goodly company,
Her ioyous presence and sweet company
Vnto her vew, and company vnsoght;
To search the secret haunts of Dianes company.
But if I catch him in this company,
Her deare Adonis ioyous company,
With many of the Gods in company,
It was, with whom in company he yode,
Approch to her, ne keepe her company,
And company at meat, to do them more delight.
After whom marcht a iolly company,
And did suruay his goodly company:
That offer pleased all the company,
There did Typhaon with her company;
That neither could to company of th'other creepe.
So darke are earthly things compard to things diuine.
For next to death is Sleepe to be compard:
Might be compar'd to these by many parts:
Compar'd to her, that shone as Phebes light,
One day in doubt I cast for to compare,
To fill his bags, and richesse to compare;
And when her curteous deeds he did compare,
That was on earth not easie to compare;
Yet no man to them can his carefull paines compare.
Cannot with noble Britomart compare,
Liues none this day, that may with her compare
And with her beautie bountie did compare,
The image of the antique world compare,
And then together doe them both compare.
To which what can compare?) can it compare;
To which what can compare?) can it compare;
That all her peres cannot with her compare,
Compared to the creatures in the seas entrall.
And times comparing with their accidents,
A thing without the compas of my wit:
Vpon his card and compas firmes his eye,
A brasen wall in compas to compile
Made a calme shadow far in compasse round:
That I may cast to compasse your reliefe,
With comely compasse, and compacture strong,
Withouten compasse, or withouten card,
To compasse thy desire, and find that loued knight.
To be the compasse of his kingdomes seat:
When for to compasse Philliras hard loue,
And like a silken veile in compasse round
Within the compasse of that Islands space;
Contayned be, and in small compasse hild?
But alwaies doe their powre within iust compasse pen.
That we may compasse this our enterprize?
Of all that on this earthly compasse wonnes:
Or in the compasse of his clouches tooke;
That all about did close the compasse of his eye.
And like a girlond did in compasse stemme:
Still winneth way, ne hath her compasse lost:
And was with dread and horrour compassed around.
Like highest heauen compassed around,
But like a girlond compassed the hight,
That ere the yeare his course had compassid,
That moues more deare compassion of mind,
Her hart gan melt in great compassion,
Her feeling speeches some compassion moued
They in compassion of her tender youth,
That may compassion of their euils moue?
For great compassion of their sorrow, bid
With womanish compassion of her plaint,
My hart doth melt with meere compassion,
Deepe indignation and compassion frayle
The deare compassion of whose bitter fit
With deare compassion deeply did emmoue,
The peoples great compassion vnto her allure.
Was inly touched with compassion deare,
And feele compassion of his euill plight
His deepe compassion of her dolefull stound,
Without compassion of her cruell smarts:
Was touched with compassion entire,
Without compassion cruelly he threw;
His care more then her owne compassionate,
Is not empierst with deepe compassiowne,
Of this great gardin, compast with a mound,
Might by the witch or by her sonne compast:
So sore he sowst him on the compast creast,
Whom to auenge, she had this Knight from far co[m]peld.
At last he was compeld to cry perforse,
Them both attonce compeld with courage bold,
And soone compeld to hearken vnto peace:
Ne may loue be compeld by maisterie;
Sith late mischaunce had her compeld to chaunge
That this faire many were compeld at last,
He was compeld to seeke some refuge neare,
Then tooke he that same Dwarfe, and him compeld
All this accord, to which he Crudor had compeld.
Compeld him soone the spoyle adowne to lay.
That would compell all nations to adore,
Wyld beasts in yron yokes he would compell;
So him dismounted low, he did compell
knightes to flight compell.
For the large leape, which Debon did compell
And trumpets sound to cease did them compell.
And to alight on foote her algates did compell.
He thought her to compell by crueltie and awe.
Do you by duresse him compell thereto,
From that foule monster, which did her compell
Doth them compell to worke, to earne their meat,
And each to other calling, did compell
And roring horribly, did him compell
That shortly them compelled to retrate,
Thereto compelled through hart-murdring paine,
Not by strong hand compelled thereunto,
Compelled were themselues a while to rest,
Compelling her, wher she would not, by force,
And to his law compels all creatures to obay.
As in the smoky forge it was compilde,
Your curteous tongue, his prayses to compile,
A brasen wall in compas to compile
So great perfections did in her compile,
It was complaind, that thou hadst done great tort
Accomplished, that many deare complaind:
That piteously complaind her carefull grieffe,
Do for the milkie mothers want complaine,
And to that mighty Princesse did complaine
And hauing not complaine, and hauing it vpbraid?
Yet many Ladies faire did oft complaine,
His Faery Queene, for whom he did complaine:
But by the way he greatly gan complaine
She sweetly heard complaine, both how and what
The wofull husbandman doth lowd complaine,
Ne lesse thereat did Paridell complaine,
So feelingly her case she did complaine,
Into some pit, where she him heares complaine,
Nor vnto any meaner to complaine,
Hard is the case, the which ye doe complaine;
Whom pitying to heare so sore complaine,
And shamefull Knight, of whom she did complaine.
Such as it was, ne did of want complaine,
Gan to complaine of great discourtesie,
And often did of loue, and oft of lucke complaine.
That hauing small, yet doe I not complaine
That made him scoule, and pout, and oft complaine
Ne wight he found, to whom he might complaine,
And vnto them complained, how that he
Al those great wrongs, the which that mayd complained
Her therewith yirks, and still when she complaines,
Behold, Sir, how your pitifull complaint
All which complaint when Marinell had heard,
That womanish complaints she did represse,
And pittifull complaints, which there she made,
Thereat she sighed deepe, and after thus complaynd.
But Paridell complaynd, that his late fight
And oft complayn'd of fate, and Fortune oft defyde.
Complayning, how with his empoysned shot
Complayning of her cruell Paramoure,
Great sorts of louers piteously complayning,
To whom complayning her afflicted plight,
In vaine complayning, to be so abused.
His wofull Ladie, piteously complayning
Complayning out on me, that would not on them rew.
Supplide her sobbing breaches with sad complement.
So all did make in her a perfect complement.
And all the complements of curtesie:
A comely knight, all arm'd in complete wize,
Of swarth complexion, and of crabbed hew,
Of the sunbeames in moyst complexion,
Meet for her temper and complexion:
Which in his cold complexion do breed
Through goodly mixture of complexions dew;
And kept from complishing the faith, which I did owe.
They did this complot twixt them selues deuise,
Goodly comportance each to other beare,
But soone she did her countenance compose,
The Priest him selfe a garland doth compose
And life enioy for any composition.
Withouten dowre or composition;
And pompous pride eftsoones he did compound;
Till vniuersall peace compound all ciuill iarre.
To put to sea, with whom they did compound,
They did their counsels now in one compound;
That nought but gall and venim comprehended,
Comprised be, I will them in another tell.
But that the same could one of these comprize.
What meaning mote those vncouth words comprize,
Vpgath'ring, in her bosome she comprized,
He the six Islands, comprouinciall
Of strong compulsion, and streight violence,
So sensibly compyld, that in the same
Thus when the Prince had perfectly compylde
And with lewd poems, which he did compyle;
As that renowmed Poet them compyled,
Then Griffyth Conan also shall vp reare
By errant Sprights, but from all men conceald:
I thether went where I did long conceale
She did conceale, and murder her owne mynd;
(Vnlesse thou in these woods thy selfe conceale,
So lay him in her charet, close in night concealed.
Litle she weend, that loue he close concealed;
Least did she thinke, that which he most concealed,
But double griefs afflict concealing harts,
Which long concealing in her couert brest,
Of his old loue, conceau'd in secret brest,
What comfort can I wofull wretch conceaue,
To steale a snatch of amorous conceipt,
Which vaine conceipt now nourishing no more,
In her conceiptfull mynd, that this faire Mayd
That she conceiu'd; and trebling the dew time,
And of him selfe great hope and helpe conceiu'd,
Conceiu'd a bold deuise, and thus bespake;
Conceiu'd these infants, and how them she bare,
Vnwares she them conceiu'd, vnwares she bore:
And curteise vse conceiu'd affection bace,
That soone they life conceiu'd, & forth in flames did fly.
He soone allayd that Knights conceiu'd displeasure,
And many gealous thoughts conceiu'd in vaine,
Conceiue such soueraine glory, and great bountihed?
Doe life conceiue and quickned are by kynd:
Loue to conceiue in her disdainfull brest;
He gan in mind conceiue a fit reliefe
Ne yours conceiue, ne but by tokens speake:
She did conceiue, through care of womanhood,
And euer by her lookes conceiued her intent.
And tell the cause of your conceiued paine.
Whiles cause not well conceiued ye mistake.
Yet cold through feare, and old conceiued dreads;
And quench the brond of his conceiued ire.
Her fickle hart conceiued hasty fire,
She bore withouten paine, that she conceiued
His nimble feet to her conceiued feare,
Great comfort of her presence he conceiued,
Ah gentle knight, whose deepe conceiued griefe
Conceiued had, to see her owne dear knight,
Conceiued by a ring, which she him sent,
She inly yet conceiued great disgrace.
The cause of her conceiued maladie,
Conceiued close in her beguiled hart,
For very fell despight, which she conceiued,
Scarse so conceiued in her iealous thought,
But this, what euer euill she conceiued,
Begets and eke conceiues, ne needeth other none.
Conceiueth fire, the heauens it doth fill
They both conceiuing hope of comfort glad,
Whereof conceiuing shame and foule disgrace,
Whereof conceiuing, she in time forth brought
The trustie Mayd, conceiuing her intent,
Faire Emiline, conceiuing then great feare
Which all that while I closely had conceld;
From peoples knowledge labour'd to concele.
Such Musicke is wise words with time concented,
And her conception of the ioyous Prime,
So straunge ensample of conception;
His be that care, whom most it doth concerne,
But since it me concernes, my selfe to clere,
Who wondrous things concerning our welfare,
Through dolorous despaire, which she conceyued,
Which might concluded be by mutuall consent.
The maister Cooke was cald Concoction,
But louely concord, and most sacred peace
And with that golden chaine of concord tyde.
How she might ouerthrow the things that Concord wrought.
With which it blessed Concord hath together tide.
Concord she cleeped was in common reed,
He let to grow and griesly to concrew,
By wicked doome condemn'd, a wretched death to die.
She him condemn'd, as trustlesse and vntrew:
The whiles I him condemne, and deeme his paine,
Theseus condemned to endlesse slouth by law,
Condemned to that Dongeon mercilesse,
May backe returne, but is condemned to be drent.
Ne cared as a coward so to be condemned.
Thereto they both did franckly condiscend,
Whose bad condition yet it doth retaine,
In which condition I right now did stand.
But blotted with condition vile and base,
Imposd on it, with many a hard condition,
But to release his former foule condition.
As graunt me liue in like condition;
For euery substance is conditioned
With like conditions to their kinds applyde:
And to her iust conditions of faire peace to heare.
All shap't according their conditions,
That man to hard conditions to bind,
And also far vnlike conditions has;
And in conditions to be loath'd no lesse:
But O vaine iudgement, and conditions vaine,
But these conditions doe to him propound,
Scorning her offers and conditions vaine;
Began the streight conditions to propound,
For his faire vsage and conditions sound,
With these conditions, which I will propound:
Betweene them both, by conduct of his blade.
Gaue them safe conduct, till to end they came:
Guyde ye my footing, and conduct me well
Withouten guide, her to conduct aright,
To wend with him, and be his conduct trew
So he them streight conducted to his Lord,
And they her forth conducted, where they might
For safe conducting of his sickely Dame,
Till by a conduit pipe it thence were brought:
And diuersly conferred of their case,
As one that would confesse, yet faine would it denie.
Who being askt, accordingly confessed all.
Confest, how Philemon her wrought to chaunge her weede.
For his bold feats and hardy confidence,
Then vertues might, and values confidence,
Most confidence and hope of happie speed,
I was emboldned with more confidence;
Who counsels him through confidence of might,
The better to confirme her fearelesse confidence.
Who euer thinkes through confidence of might,
But kept her place with courage confident,
The Cornish and the Deuonish confines;
So settled he his kingdome, and confirmd his right.
So peace being confirm'd amongst them all,
Which to confirme, and fast to bind their league,
Yet ought mens good endeuours them confirme,
The better to confirme her fearelesse confidence.
And that of Cambry king confirmed late,
The lucklesse conflict with the Gyant stout,
And combrous conflict, which they did sustaine,
This cruell conflict raised thereabout,
Such was the conflict of those cruell Brigants there.
In that same conflict (woe is me) befell
Their frayle amazed senses did confound:
Defend thine honour, and thy foes confound:
Through passing brightnesse, which did quite co[n]found
Do arme your selfe against that day, them to confound.
But realmes and rulers thou doest both confound,
Broke their rude troupes, and orders did confound,
In Thebes, which Alexander did confound;
Where so he heares, that any doth confound
And all the world confound with cruelty,
The feeble senses wholly did confound,
Wherewith the hellish fiends he doth confound.
And curse his God, that did him so confound;
And all the world confound with wide vprore,
Through these his slights he many doth confound,
And eke him selfe did threaten to confound,
And right and wrong most cruelly confound:
To worke his vtter shame, and throughly him confound.
And those two Sarazins confounded late,
Much was the man confounded in his mind,
By her beguyled, and confounded quight:
So all confounded and disordered there.
Confounds both land & seas, and skyes doth ouercast.
Confusd with womens cries, and shouts of boyes,
Flocking together in confusde array,
He them encountred, a confused rout,
Which suddeine horrour and confused cry,
And this great Vniuerse seemd one confused mas.
As smoke and sulphure mingled with confused strife.
Greatly confused in behauioure;
Ten thousand wayes he cast in his confused thought.
And after them a rude confused rout
His foe confused through his sodaine fall,
A while about her with confused eye;
As one adaw'd, and halfe confused stood;
She was confused in her troublous thought,
But a soft murmure, and confused sound
Confused, did the ayre with terror fill,
All on confused heapes themselues assay,
There lay she couered with confused preasse
Where when confusedly they came, they fownd
Least thy foolhardize worke thy sad confusion.
And many hath to foule confusion brought.
Vnto his last confusion to bring,
Into this world, to worke confusion,
That thorough rude confusion of the rout,
And there was caught to her confusion.
I onely scapt through great confusione
So courteous conge both did giue and take,
So taking courteous conge he behight,
They courteous conge tooke, and forth together yode.
Was purest snow in massie mould congeald,
Of bloudy gore congeal'd about them stood,
His cruell wounds with cruddy bloud congealed,
That sight thereof bred cold congealed feare:
And with dry drops congealed in her eye,
The Christall humour stood congealed rownd;
Yet still he wasted, as the snow congealed,
The sight whereof in his congealed flesh,
Congealed litle drops, which doe the morne adore.
And vnto her his congee came to take.
Then taking Congï¿½ fÂ© of that virgin pure,
She with him bound, and Congï¿½ tooke withall.
For not to grow of nought he it coniectured.
Where singled forces faile, conioynd may gaine.
And them coniur'd by some well knowen token,
And them coniure t'auenge this shamefull iniury.
Did earnestly commit, and her coniure,
And them coniure vpon eternall paine,
When those gainst states and kingdomes do coniure,
Doest conquer greatest conquerors on ground,
For though sweet loue to conquer glorious be,
After the Paynim brethren conquer'd were,
For whylome they haue conquerd sea and land,
Whom yet he conquer'd not by bloudie fight,
Bearing the shield which I had conquerd late,
Vnto the Castle, which they conquerd had.
Of all this land, late conquer'd by his sword
Though conquered now he lie on lowly land,
And seem'd himselfe as conquered to yield.
That he in ods of armes was conquered;
And hong their conquered armes for more defame
Corineus conquered, and cruelly did slay.
And taught her first how to be conquered;
Of this sweet Island, neuer conquered,
And the spoile of the countrey conquered
And her white Palfrey hauing conquered
He brought to her in bands, as conquered
From slaughter of the Giaunts conquered;
That Albion had conquered first by warlike feat.
Hath conquered you anew in second fight:
And now by this the noble Conqueresse
Doest conquer greatest conquerors on ground,
And mightie Conquerors, in royall state,
Vnto that doughtie Conquerour they came,
The Conquerour nought cared him to slay,
Thus now alone he conquerour remaines;
The Sarazins shield, signe of the conqueroure.
The Laurell, meed of mightie Conquerours
From mightie kings and conquerours in warre,
And girlond of the mighty Conquerours,
Of mighty Conquerours and Captaines strong,
The conquest yours, I yours, the shield, and glory yours.
For greater conquest of hard loue he gaynes,
Thenceforth the suit of earthly conquest shonne,
That had atchieu'd so great a conquest by his might.
For those, which Hercules with conquest bold
That of this lands first conquest did deuize,
His goodly conquest of the golden fleece,
Subdew, through conquest of your wondrous might,
As if the conquest his he surely wist.
Scudamour doth his conquest tell,
Yet quaile in conquest of that land of gold.
Who all the West with equall conquest wonne,
No fayrer conquest, then that with goodwill is gayned.
Till I the conquest of my will recouer.
From his late conquest, which he gotten had.
That rather seem'd the conquest of his might,
